HEADWORD: Syndrome
<hw>Syn"dro*me</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., from Gr.
<?/; <grk>sy`n</grk> with + <?/ a course, a running.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Concurrence.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Glanvill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A group of symptoms occurring
together that are characteristic and indicative of some underlying
cause, such as a disease.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>generally, a pattern of characteristics or behaviors
occurring together, that are sufficiently common and distinctive to
indicate that they are due to a known cause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Syndyasmian</ent>⟦br⟧
